# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: VargaMarionPath | Scene: VargaPath7
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "A month had passed since Thomas had been kidnapped by Marion and the old houses had declared their revolt."
    new "A month had passed since Thomas had been kidnapped by Marion and the old houses had declared their revolt."

    old "An entire month where she had no idea how he was doing."
    new "An entire month where she had no idea how he was doing."

    old "Sarah had spent her entire life in the proximity of her brother. The idea of not knowing if he was safe was alien and unsettling."
    new "Sarah had spent her entire life in the proximity of her brother. The idea of not knowing if he was safe was alien and unsettling."

    old "With every day, Sarah grew more worried."
    new "With every day, Sarah grew more worried."

    old "Part of her knew that their enemy would use reason. Her brother was more valuable to them as a hostage than he was dead."
    new "Part of her knew that their enemy would use reason. Her brother was more valuable to them as a hostage than he was dead."

    old "But another part of her also knew that mistakes could happen. And sometimes, people acted not out of reason, but emotion."
    new "But another part of her also knew that mistakes could happen. And sometimes, people acted not out of reason, but emotion."

    old "Regardless, Sarah knew her brother would only truly be safe when he was back home with her at Castle Reinmeer."
    new "Regardless, Sarah knew her brother would only truly be safe when he was back home with her at Castle Reinmeer."

    old "As part of this, Sarah had taken to accompanying small army units on patrol."
    new "As part of this, Sarah had taken to accompanying small army units on patrol."

    old "Sarah didn't think she could so much as swing a sword without injuring herself, but she had come to know there was a difference between her reports and the reality on the ground."
    new "Sarah didn't think she could so much as swing a sword without injuring herself, but she had come to know there was a difference between her reports and the reality on the ground."

    old "Together with her husband Varga, she now tried to go on patrol in the border provinces whenever she could."
    new "Together with her husband Varga, she now tried to go on patrol in the border provinces whenever she could."

    old "Already, she had learned a great deal from her experience."
    new "Already, she had learned a great deal from her experience."

    old "She learned how important understanding the lay of the land was. The difficulties of logistics. And how the commonfolk seemed to almost resent the presence of the soldiers."
    new "She learned how important understanding the lay of the land was. The difficulties of logistics. And how the commonfolk seemed to almost resent the presence of the soldiers."

    old "It was the latter part that had surprised her the most."
    new "It was the latter part that had surprised her the most."

    old "Sarah always believed that the people of Rosanna were as one, unified, but in reality, the common people mostly just wanted to be left alone."
    new "Sarah always believed that the people of Rosanna were as one, unified, but in reality, the common people mostly just wanted to be left alone."

    old "To most of them, soldiers only meant bad news."
    new "To most of them, soldiers only meant bad news."

    old "Things were particularly bad on the border territories, where most of the fighting and raiding took place."
    new "Things were particularly bad on the border territories, where most of the fighting and raiding took place."

    old "Seeing the devastation made Sarah want to end the war as fast as she could."
    new "Seeing the devastation made Sarah want to end the war as fast as she could."

    old "Today was the second day on patrol and Sarah and Varga had tagged along with the Grey Falcon unit, a small cavalry unit whose purpose was to ride along the border towns, patrolling for possible enemy raids."
    new "Today was the second day on patrol and Sarah and Varga had tagged along with the Grey Falcon unit, a small cavalry unit whose purpose was to ride along the border towns, patrolling for possible enemy raids."

    old "In truth, their unit did not ride very far out, and though the town they came upon today was technically in the border province, it was unlikely they would have suffered any raids."
    new "In truth, their unit did not ride very far out, and though the town they came upon today was technically in the border province, it was unlikely they would have suffered any raids."

    old "Marion and his forces struck, seemingly randomly, but they never dared to attack deep into the heartland of Rosanna."
    new "Marion and his forces struck, seemingly randomly, but they never dared to attack deep into the heartland of Rosanna."

    old "Sarah had spoken to her council on many occassions, trying to make sense of their strategy."
    new "Sarah had spoken to her council on many occassions, trying to make sense of their strategy."

    old "Was it cowardice that they did not dare to strike deep, or was there some plan they did not yet understand? Not knowing made Sarah feel uneasy."
    new "Was it cowardice that they did not dare to strike deep, or was there some plan they did not yet understand? Not knowing made Sarah feel uneasy."

    old "What's this town called?"
    new "What's this town called?"

    old "Sarah walked next to Varga. Unlike her, he seemed to have a natural affinity for remembering the name of every odd person or town they came upon."
    new "Sarah walked next to Varga. Unlike her, he seemed to have a natural affinity for remembering the name of every odd person or town they came upon."

    old "It's Duskcreek."
    new "It's Duskcreek."

    old "A small town, maybe two-hundred people, if that. Mostly farmers, and a few families that work the local river for fish."
    new "A small town, maybe two-hundred people, if that. Mostly farmers, and a few families that work the local river for fish."

    old "Have they been safe so far?"
    new "Have they been safe so far?"

    old "They've been spared the worst of it."
    new "They've been spared the worst of it."

    old "Don't expect too friendly a welcome though."
    new "Don't expect too friendly a welcome though."

    old "Harvest season will be here in a few months and they're short on young men to haul in the crops."
    new "Harvest season will be here in a few months and they're short on young men to haul in the crops."

    old "Where did they go?"
    new "Where did they go?"

    old "Varga looked at her as they continued walking towards the town."
    new "Varga looked at her as they continued walking towards the town."

    old "Your army."
    new "Your army."

    old "We had to call upon the nobles to raise their armies. The nobles, in turn, raise their armies from the common folk."
    new "We had to call upon the nobles to raise their armies. The nobles, in turn, raise their armies from the common folk."

    old "They get paid, sure, and if they survive they'll win some glory, but for the most part it leaves the economies of these small towns in shambles."
    new "They get paid, sure, and if they survive they'll win some glory, but for the most part it leaves the economies of these small towns in shambles."

    old "Without young men to work the field, at least a good part of the crops will rot in the field."
    new "Without young men to work the field, at least a good part of the crops will rot in the field."

    old "Sarah was quiet as she listened to her husband explain the ways of the world. The real world, that real people have to live in."
    new "Sarah was quiet as she listened to her husband explain the ways of the world. The real world, that real people have to live in."

    old "She had never gone hungry in her life."
    new "She had never gone hungry in her life."

    old "Most of them don't know it yet, but months from now there will be a shortage of food, possibly even a famine, depending on how long the war drags on for."
    new "Most of them don't know it yet, but months from now there will be a shortage of food, possibly even a famine, depending on how long the war drags on for."

    old "A famine? That's horrible...we can't allow that to happen."
    new "A famine? That's horrible...we can't allow that to happen."

    old "If we win the war before then, we can use the royal treasury to import food, but if the war is still going on by then..."
    new "If we win the war before then, we can use the royal treasury to import food, but if the war is still going on by then..."

    old "Spending money to feed peasants was easy enough to sell in times of peace, but during war, every coin went to the army."
    new "Spending money to feed peasants was easy enough to sell in times of peace, but during war, every coin went to the army."

    old "I wonder if Marion knows how much suffering he's causing."
    new "I wonder if Marion knows how much suffering he's causing."

    old "I doubt he ever thinks much of anyone else other than his noble friends."
    new "I doubt he ever thinks much of anyone else other than his noble friends."

    old "You sound confident."
    new "You sound confident."

    old "I grew up in a town not so different from this one. Our noble lord left us to rot as soon as it was convenient to him."
    new "I grew up in a town not so different from this one. Our noble lord left us to rot as soon as it was convenient to him."

    old "Every year when it was time to pay our taxes, he loved to talk about what our role was and what his role was."
    new "Every year when it was time to pay our taxes, he loved to talk about what our role was and what his role was."

    old "He'd talk about how important the nobles were, to govern the land, to keep us safe. But when the townspeople revolted, he all but begged the army to put them down."
    new "He'd talk about how important the nobles were, to govern the land, to keep us safe. But when the townspeople revolted, he all but begged the army to put them down."

    old "Did you ever consider joining them? In the uprising, I mean."
    new "Did you ever consider joining them? In the uprising, I mean."

    old "Sarah was careful to speak about the subject. She knew that her husband didn't enjoy talking about the very military victory that had earned him his title."
    new "Sarah was careful to speak about the subject. She knew that her husband didn't enjoy talking about the very military victory that had earned him his title."

    old "Varga was quiet for a while as they continued walking. Then he spoke."
    new "Varga was quiet for a while as they continued walking. Then he spoke."

    old "Sarah...I..."
    new "Sarah...I..."

    old "I organized the defense, I put down the rebellion...but I won't lie and say that I didn't understand why they took up arms."
    new "I organized the defense, I put down the rebellion...but I won't lie and say that I didn't understand why they took up arms."

    old "Then why did you not join them?"
    new "Then why did you not join them?"

    old "It was strategy. Same reason I defeated them."
    new "It was strategy. Same reason I defeated them."

    old "I could see from the start that they would lose. Not that same day, or even that same week, but I could see months in the future."
    new "I could see from the start that they would lose. Not that same day, or even that same week, but I could see months in the future."

    old "They were done the moment they picked up their weapons."
    new "They were done the moment they picked up their weapons."

    old "But that's the problem with people. They rarely see beyond their immediate moment."
    new "But that's the problem with people. They rarely see beyond their immediate moment."

    old "The peasants that took part in the uprising had great success in their first weeks, so they all but imagined their victory was certain."
    new "The peasants that took part in the uprising had great success in their first weeks, so they all but imagined their victory was certain."

    old "But unlike them, my father had taken me to the provincial capital."
    new "But unlike them, my father had taken me to the provincial capital."

    old "I had seen the armies of Rosanna. The heavy cladded steel knights, horses tall enough to tower over a man."
    new "I had seen the armies of Rosanna. The heavy cladded steel knights, horses tall enough to tower over a man."

    old "I just knew it was only a matter of time before they'd get crushed, and so I picked the smarter strategy."
    new "I just knew it was only a matter of time before they'd get crushed, and so I picked the smarter strategy."

    old "That's also why I don't really like to talk about it."
    new "That's also why I don't really like to talk about it."

    old "It makes for a fine story of heroism to most in the capital, but for me, it meant slaughtering the people that were my friends."
    new "It makes for a fine story of heroism to most in the capital, but for me, it meant slaughtering the people that were my friends."

    old "Some of the very same people I put into the ground, only a season prior, had celebrated the annual harvest festival with me."
    new "Some of the very same people I put into the ground, only a season prior, had celebrated the annual harvest festival with me."

    old "After that, they gave me my title, and I never looked back."
    new "After that, they gave me my title, and I never looked back."

    old "The peace returned, but nobody could really forgive me for what I had done. They'd never say anything, but you could see it in their eyes."
    new "The peace returned, but nobody could really forgive me for what I had done. They'd never say anything, but you could see it in their eyes."

    old "I had sided against them, and even in defeat, they would never forgive that."
    new "I had sided against them, and even in defeat, they would never forgive that."

    old "There was a long silence between them."
    new "There was a long silence between them."

    old "It brought you to the capital. To Castle Reinmeer..."
    new "It brought you to the capital. To Castle Reinmeer..."

    old "To me."
    new "To me."

    old "She smiled at her husband, and he smiled back at her."
    new "She smiled at her husband, and he smiled back at her."

    old "Yes, I suppose I shouldn't go around in pity for myself. I'm sorry."
    new "Yes, I suppose I shouldn't go around in pity for myself. I'm sorry."

    old "Sarah looped her arm through his, linking them together."
    new "Sarah looped her arm through his, linking them together."

    old "Don't apologize. I always love learning more about you."
    new "Don't apologize. I always love learning more about you."

    old "In good spirits, the loving couple and their military escort arrived in the small town proper."
    new "In good spirits, the loving couple and their military escort arrived in the small town proper."

    old "Most of the peasants dropped their work and watched the soldiers enter the town square."
    new "Most of the peasants dropped their work and watched the soldiers enter the town square."

    old "Sarah drew her own share of attention. Most did not know who she was, but her clothes were enough to tell them she was important."
    new "Sarah drew her own share of attention. Most did not know who she was, but her clothes were enough to tell them she was important."

    old "They watched as the soldiers rode off along different roads, gathering up everyone that lived in the town."
    new "They watched as the soldiers rode off along different roads, gathering up everyone that lived in the town."

    old "Not long after, the entire town had been gathered."
    new "Not long after, the entire town had been gathered."

    old "Sarah knew that the soldiers were all on their best behavior when she was around, and even so, she felt uneasy at how crude they were."
    new "Sarah knew that the soldiers were all on their best behavior when she was around, and even so, she felt uneasy at how crude they were."

    old "The soldiers yelled their commands at the townsfolk, shoved them when their answers did not come fast enough, some even destroyed small bits of property."
    new "The soldiers yelled their commands at the townsfolk, shoved them when their answers did not come fast enough, some even destroyed small bits of property."

    old "No wonder they hate us, Sarah realized."
    new "No wonder they hate us, Sarah realized."

    old "Had any people come to her house and treated her family as these soldiers did, she surely would have hated them the same."
    new "Had any people come to her house and treated her family as these soldiers did, she surely would have hated them the same."

    old "And yet...the truth was that her country had been torn apart by Marion and his band of traitors."
    new "And yet...the truth was that her country had been torn apart by Marion and his band of traitors."

    old "She wished she could order her soldiers back home, leave these people in peace, but she would never yield to Marion, or abandon her brother."
    new "She wished she could order her soldiers back home, leave these people in peace, but she would never yield to Marion, or abandon her brother."

    old "And that meant keeping her army mobilized. And that these people would suffer."
    new "And that meant keeping her army mobilized. And that these people would suffer."

    old "{i}It tore her heart apart, and still she forced herself to watch. Don't look away from what you cause, she told herself.{/i}"
    new "{i}It tore her heart apart, and still she forced herself to watch. Don't look away from what you cause, she told herself.{/i}"

    old "Suddenly, a loud scream rang out from the far side of the square."
    new "Suddenly, a loud scream rang out from the far side of the square."

    old "At first, it was hard for Sarah to see what was happening through all the soldiers and townsfolk."
    new "At first, it was hard for Sarah to see what was happening through all the soldiers and townsfolk."

    old "Her husband had instinctively placed himself between her and the yelling. She loved him for it, even though she didn't think that she was in any real danger."
    new "Her husband had instinctively placed himself between her and the yelling. She loved him for it, even though she didn't think that she was in any real danger."

    old "The crowd parted as Sarah watched two soldiers drag a young woman out towards her."
    new "The crowd parted as Sarah watched two soldiers drag a young woman out towards her."

    old "She loudly objected to her handling, screaming and struggling the whole way."
    new "She loudly objected to her handling, screaming and struggling the whole way."

    old "The soldiers threw the girl down in front of her and Varga, landing in the mud, the young woman's clothes were caked in it."
    new "The soldiers threw the girl down in front of her and Varga, landing in the mud, the young woman's clothes were caked in it."

    old "Your highness, we caught this one after she just hurled a rock at us. What do you want us to do with her?"
    new "Your highness, we caught this one after she just hurled a rock at us. What do you want us to do with her?"

    old "Sarah could hear the murmurs spread through the crowd."
    new "Sarah could hear the murmurs spread through the crowd."

    old "If they hadn't known who she was before, the soldier had just given it away."
    new "If they hadn't known who she was before, the soldier had just given it away."

    old "Let go of me!"
    new "Let go of me!"

    old "Sarah walked up to her as she was still on the ground. With guards everywhere, she was smart enough not to try anything, or so Sarah hoped."
    new "Sarah walked up to her as she was still on the ground. With guards everywhere, she was smart enough not to try anything, or so Sarah hoped."

    old "Is that true?"
    new "Is that true?"

    old "That I threw a rock? Pff, it wasn't a rock, a pebble, maybe."
    new "That I threw a rock? Pff, it wasn't a rock, a pebble, maybe."

    old "Why did you do that?"
    new "Why did you do that?"

    old "Because you come in here all high and mighty with your army of goons, harassing everyone in town."
    new "Because you come in here all high and mighty with your army of goons, harassing everyone in town."

    old "We didn't do anything! We didn't rebel, we're just farming, minding our own business, it's you and yours who come up here and stir shit up!"
    new "We didn't do anything! We didn't rebel, we're just farming, minding our own business, it's you and yours who come up here and stir shit up!"

    old "My brother got drafted to fight in your stupid pointless war!"
    new "My brother got drafted to fight in your stupid pointless war!"

    old "Sarah could hear the crowd grow restless. It was clear the young woman didn't just speak for herself."
    new "Sarah could hear the crowd grow restless. It was clear the young woman didn't just speak for herself."

    old "Still, from the corner of her eyes, she could see the soldiers stare at her."
    new "Still, from the corner of her eyes, she could see the soldiers stare at her."

    old "This woman had attacked them, admitted it even. The soldiers would lose respect for her if she let her get away with it."
    new "This woman had attacked them, admitted it even. The soldiers would lose respect for her if she let her get away with it."

    old "Let her go with a warning."
    new "Let her go with a warning."

    old "Sarah did not have it in her heart to add to the many burdens of the townsfolk."
    new "Sarah did not have it in her heart to add to the many burdens of the townsfolk."

    old "She waved her hand at the soldiers."
    new "She waved her hand at the soldiers."

    old "Release her."
    new "Release her."

    old "Yes, Princess."
    new "Yes, Princess."

    old "They honored her command, but Sarah could see she had lost some of their respect."
    new "They honored her command, but Sarah could see she had lost some of their respect."

    old "Thank you, Princess! Thank you for your mercy!"
    new "Thank you, Princess! Thank you for your mercy!"

    old "She watched her leap up to his feet and run off, clearly not wishing to risk her good luck by staying here any longer."
    new "She watched her leap up to his feet and run off, clearly not wishing to risk her good luck by staying here any longer."

    old "The townsfolk murmured somewhat, but Sarah wasn't sure if they approved or if they were upset at missing out on a show."
    new "The townsfolk murmured somewhat, but Sarah wasn't sure if they approved or if they were upset at missing out on a show."

    old "She didn't care, either way."
    new "She didn't care, either way."

    old "She knew she had done the right thing. Punishing a young woman over some minor inconvenience was pointless cruelty."
    new "She knew she had done the right thing. Punishing a young woman over some minor inconvenience was pointless cruelty."

    old "That cruelty was at the root of the problem."
    new "That cruelty was at the root of the problem."

    old "Everything in this country seemed to operate on one group of people holding another down."
    new "Everything in this country seemed to operate on one group of people holding another down."

    old "The old houses had rebelled against her family, specifically because they feared that her family would undo even a fraction of that hierarchy."
    new "The old houses had rebelled against her family, specifically because they feared that her family would undo even a fraction of that hierarchy."

    old "They lived and breathed in a world of pointless cruelty and oppression, it was their oxygen."
    new "They lived and breathed in a world of pointless cruelty and oppression, it was their oxygen."

    old "So what did it make her if she did the same as them? Just the stronger tyrant?"
    new "So what did it make her if she did the same as them? Just the stronger tyrant?"

    old "If this war was worth fighting, and Sarah believed that it was, then it was because she and her family offered something better."
    new "If this war was worth fighting, and Sarah believed that it was, then it was because she and her family offered something better."

    old "A nation where ordinary people did not have to live in fear of its own soldiers and nobles."
    new "A nation where ordinary people did not have to live in fear of its own soldiers and nobles."

    old "Make an example out of her."
    new "Make an example out of her."

    old "Sarah knew she could not just be allowed to leave."
    new "Sarah knew she could not just be allowed to leave."

    old "She had attacked the soldiers, her soldiers, and the girl even proudly admitted it."
    new "She had attacked the soldiers, her soldiers, and the girl even proudly admitted it."

    old "If she let her go with no punishment, who knew if the story would spread, and next time one person with a rock would turn out to be a dozen."
    new "If she let her go with no punishment, who knew if the story would spread, and next time one person with a rock would turn out to be a dozen."

    old "No, she concluded. This would end here."
    new "No, she concluded. This would end here."

    old "Armsman!"
    new "Armsman!"

    old "Yes, Princess?"
    new "Yes, Princess?"

    old "Strip this woman, tie her to a pole, and flog her in the square."
    new "Strip this woman, tie her to a pole, and flog her in the square."

    old "As you command!"
    new "As you command!"

    old "Sarah could see the attitude of her soldiers shift. They saw her as having their backs."
    new "Sarah could see the attitude of her soldiers shift. They saw her as having their backs."

    old "No! Please! You can't do this, you don't have the right!"
    new "No! Please! You can't do this, you don't have the right!"

    old "But Sarah did have the right, as the young woman would soon learn."
    new "But Sarah did have the right, as the young woman would soon learn."

    old "She struggled again as the soldiers seized her and began tying her to a stake."
    new "She struggled again as the soldiers seized her and began tying her to a stake."

    old "Her rousing speech was now quickly forgotten as the townsfolk saw her beg and cry for a mercy she would not receive."
    new "Her rousing speech was now quickly forgotten as the townsfolk saw her beg and cry for a mercy she would not receive."

    old "With ease, the soldiers ripped off her cheap clothes and tossed them to the mud, leaving the woman naked and bound to the pillar."
    new "With ease, the soldiers ripped off her cheap clothes and tossed them to the mud, leaving the woman naked and bound to the pillar."

    old "A laughter ran through the people watching."
    new "A laughter ran through the people watching."

    old "How quickly they turn on her, Sarah realized."
    new "How quickly they turn on her, Sarah realized."

    old "A soldier approached, whip ready in hand."
    new "A soldier approached, whip ready in hand."

    old "Flogging was not an unknown punishment in the Rosannan military, so the tools as well as the practice were easy to produce."
    new "Flogging was not an unknown punishment in the Rosannan military, so the tools as well as the practice were easy to produce."

    old "However, Sarah knew, for a peasant such a punishment was a rarity."
    new "However, Sarah knew, for a peasant such a punishment was a rarity."

    old "And the young woman had quickly gone from revolutionary to a town spectacle."
    new "And the young woman had quickly gone from revolutionary to a town spectacle."

    old "The first blow brought the crowd to silence."
    new "The first blow brought the crowd to silence."

    old "The snapping of the whip was a violent sound, but the effect on the young woman's body was no less so."
    new "The snapping of the whip was a violent sound, but the effect on the young woman's body was no less so."

    old "A mist of red blood splashed out and a deep crimson trail as left across her back."
    new "A mist of red blood splashed out and a deep crimson trail as left across her back."

    old "Her body winced and she screamed out, but bound tightly, there was little space for her to move."
    new "Her body winced and she screamed out, but bound tightly, there was little space for her to move."

    old "When the second strike of the lash cut across her back, the crowd discovered its amusement again."
    new "When the second strike of the lash cut across her back, the crowd discovered its amusement again."

    old "In her heart she found the affair horrid, but she forced herself to bear a cold gaze as she looked on."
    new "In her heart she found the affair horrid, but she forced herself to bear a cold gaze as she looked on."

    old "And she did look on, for she knew she had caused this too."
    new "And she did look on, for she knew she had caused this too."

    old "As the whipping continued, the young woman's flailing and cries slowly died out as her body fell to exhaustion."
    new "As the whipping continued, the young woman's flailing and cries slowly died out as her body fell to exhaustion."

    old "The pain mixed with the public humiliation was too much, and she soon fainted."
    new "The pain mixed with the public humiliation was too much, and she soon fainted."

    old "When the last whip struck her body, she did not even so much as move or make a sound."
    new "When the last whip struck her body, she did not even so much as move or make a sound."

    old "Flogging was cruel business, but flogging someone who could not even feel or cry out was senseless."
    new "Flogging was cruel business, but flogging someone who could not even feel or cry out was senseless."

    old "The message had been made."
    new "The message had been made."

    old "Take her down and mend her wounds."
    new "Take her down and mend her wounds."

    old "At once, my princess!"
    new "At once, my princess!"

    old "Moving as one, the soldiers easily untied the young woman and carefully placed her on a stretcher, applying bandages to the very wounds they had just caused."
    new "Moving as one, the soldiers easily untied the young woman and carefully placed her on a stretcher, applying bandages to the very wounds they had just caused."

    old "She would heal, Sarah knew."
    new "She would heal, Sarah knew."

    old "It would take weeks before the pain in her back had fully faded, and the scars would probably last a lifetime, but she would survive this injury."
    new "It would take weeks before the pain in her back had fully faded, and the scars would probably last a lifetime, but she would survive this injury."

    old "Lasting longer than the pain, and possibly even the scars, would be the emotional damage."
    new "Lasting longer than the pain, and possibly even the scars, would be the emotional damage."

    old "But then again, that had been the point. To forever snuff out any hint of resistance."
    new "But then again, that had been the point. To forever snuff out any hint of resistance."

    old "Because it was resistance and rebellion that had brought her to this point. Weakness and a tolerance for weak loyalty."
    new "Because it was resistance and rebellion that had brought her to this point. Weakness and a tolerance for weak loyalty."

    old "Sarah told herself, she would unite the country through strength, but she would also root out all hints of disloyalty."
    new "Sarah told herself, she would unite the country through strength, but she would also root out all hints of disloyalty."

    old "Peace, both for her family and the ordinary people, could only come by hunting down the traitors."
    new "Peace, both for her family and the ordinary people, could only come by hunting down the traitors."

    old "It was ugly business, but it was the business of peace."
    new "It was ugly business, but it was the business of peace."

